### WaitGroup

`sync.WaitGroup` waits for a collection of goroutines to finish.

### Basic Usage

```go
var wg sync.WaitGroup

for i := 0; i < 5; i++ {
    wg.Add(1)
    go func(id int) {
        defer wg.Done()
        fmt.Println("Worker", id)
    }(i)
}

wg.Wait() // blocks until all Done() calls
fmt.Println("All workers done")
```

### Methods

| Method | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `Add(delta int)` | Increment counter |
| `Done()` | Decrement counter (usually via defer) |
| `Wait()` | Block until counter is 0 |

### Important: Add Before Go

```go
// CORRECT: Add before starting goroutine
wg.Add(1)
go func() {
    defer wg.Done()
    // work
}()

// WRONG: Add inside goroutine (race condition)
go func() {
    wg.Add(1) // may not complete before Wait()
    defer wg.Done()
    // work
}()
```

### Negative Counter

Calling Done() more times than Add() will cause a panic.

```go
var wg sync.WaitGroup
wg.Add(1)
wg.Done()
wg.Done() // panic: negative WaitGroup counter
```

### WaitGroup with Worker Pool

```go
func worker(id int, jobs <-chan int, wg *sync.WaitGroup) {
    defer wg.Done()
    for job := range jobs {
        fmt.Printf("Worker %d processing job %d\n", id, job)
    }
}

func main() {
    const numWorkers = 3
    jobs := make(chan int, 10)
    var wg sync.WaitGroup

    // Start workers
    for i := 1; i <= numWorkers; i++ {
        wg.Add(1)
        go worker(i, jobs, &wg)
    }

    // Send jobs
    for j := 1; j <= 5; j++ {
        jobs <- j
    }
    close(jobs)

    wg.Wait()
}
```

> **Key Point:** Always call `wg.Add()` before starting the goroutine, not inside it. Always use `defer wg.Done()` to ensure the counter decrements even on panics.

codeExample:
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "sync"
)

func main() {
    var wg sync.WaitGroup

    for i := 0; i < 5; i++ {
        wg.Add(1)
        go func(id int) {
            defer wg.Done()
            fmt.Printf("Goroutine %d done\n", id)
        }(i)
    }

    wg.Wait()
    fmt.Println("All goroutines finished")
}
